1) Sliding Window: Uses two pointers moving in the same direction to track a sub-segment of data.
2) Fast and Slow Pointers: Moves two pointers at different speeds to detect cycles or find midpoints.
3) Prefix Sum: Pre-calculates cumulative totals to allow instant range-sum lookups.
4) Binary Search: A two-pointer approach that halves the search space at every step.
5) Two Pointers (Multiple Arrays): One pointer per array used to merge or compare sorted datasets.
6) Divide and Conquer: Breaks a problem into two halves recursively (like Merge Sort).
7) Backtracking: Explores all possible paths and "backtracks" when a path fails.
8) Greedy Approach: Makes the best local choice at each step to find a global solution.
9) Dynamic Programming: Breaks problems into sub-problems and stores results to avoid re-calculation.
10) BFS (Breadth-First Search): Explores a graph or tree level by level using a queue.
11) DFS (Depth-First Search): Explores a graph or tree by going as deep as possible before backtracking.
12) Monotonic Stack: Uses a stack to keep elements in a specific order (increasing or decreasing).
